Data Description

The data I choose describes the housing prices in Melbourne. I am interested in looking for a relationship between a property sale price and the year built, property size, property type, and suburb. Below the data is being filtered and presented. I am only interested in looking specific suburbs and properties larger that 50 square meters. The data can be looked at in the table below.

# Disabling scientific notation for this chunk. No numbers are that large
options(scipen=999)

#Reading in the data
data <- read.csv("Melbourne_housing_FULL.csv") %>%
  dplyr::select(Regionname, Type, YearBuilt, BuildingArea, Price, 
                Method)

#Dropping rows with incomplete data
data <- na.omit(data)

# Filtering to only look at the properties I am interested in
# Homes above 50 square meters and less than 1500 square meters
data <- data[!(data$BuildingArea<=50 | data$BuildingArea>=1500),]
# Home built only after 1900
data <- data[(data$YearBuilt>=1900),]
# Only homes that have sold
data <- data[(data$Method=='S'),]
# Filtering to only look at two suburbs
data <- data[(data$Regionname=='Northern Metropolitan') | (data$Regionname=='Southern Metropolitan')  ,]

# Renaming categorical variables
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 'u', 'Apartment'))
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 't', 'Townhouse'))
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 'h', 'House'))

#Creating a dummy variable for the housing type and region variables
data <- dummy_cols(data, select_columns = c('Type', 'Regionname'))

#Displaying the data
datatable(data[,1:5], class = 'display')
# Used for summary statistics
data$TypeDummy <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$Type))
data$RegionDummy <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$Regionname))

# Filtering to only look at the suburbs I am interested in
data <- data %>% 
  rename(
     NorthMetro = `Regionname_Northern Metropolitan`,
    SouthMetro = `Regionname_Southern Metropolitan`
    )

#Generating summary statistics for the data
YearBuilt_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(YearBuilt), sd = sd(YearBuilt), median = median(YearBuilt), IQR = IQR(YearBuilt), mode = getmode(YearBuilt), sampeSize = length(YearBuilt))
building_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(BuildingArea), sd = sd(BuildingArea), median = median(BuildingArea),   IQR = IQR(BuildingArea), mode = getmode(BuildingArea), sampeSize = length(BuildingArea))
price_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Price), sd = sd(Price), median = median(Price),   IQR = IQR(Price), mode = getmode(Price), sampeSize = length(Price))
type_summ <- data %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(TypeDummy), sd = sd(TypeDummy), median = median(TypeDummy),   IQR = IQR(TypeDummy), mode = getmode(TypeDummy), sampeSize = length(TypeDummy))
region_summ <- data %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(RegionDummy), sd = sd(RegionDummy), median = median(RegionDummy),   IQR = IQR(RegionDummy), mode = getmode(RegionDummy), sampeSize = length(RegionDummy))

#Neatly displaying the summary statistics
cols <- c('Housing Type', 'YearBuilt', 'Building Size', 'Region', 'Price')
col.Variable <- data.frame(cols)
summ1 <- rbind(type_summ, YearBuilt_summ, building_summ, region_summ, price_summ)
summ <- cbind2(col.Variable, summ1)
knitr::kable(summ, align='lccrr', caption = 'Mean, Standard Deviation, Median, and IQR of the data', col.names = c('Variable', 'Mean', 'Standard Deviation', 'Median', 'IQR', 'Mode', 'Sample Size'))

Regression Model

Now lets create a regression model. The predictors are the same as above, but the model will also include two interactions I am interested in looking at. Note that apartments and south metro are the reference groups for the two categorical predictors.

model <- lm(Price ~ YearBuilt+BuildingArea+Type_Townhouse+Type_House+NorthMetro+NorthMetro:Type_Townhouse+NorthMetro:Type_House, data=data)
coef <- coefficients(model)
anova <- anova(model)
summary <- summary(model)
ci <- as_tibble(confint(model, level=0.95))
t <- as_tibble(summary[[4]])
#Adding a variable column to table
Variable <- c('Intercept', 'Year Built', 'Home Size', 'Townhouse', 'House', 'North Metro', 'NorthMetro:Townhouse', 'NorthMetro:House')
col.Variable2 <- data.frame(Variable)
summ3 <- cbind2(col.Variable2, t)
knitr::kable(summ3, align='lccrr')

The resulting regression model is \[ \hat{Y} = 10911432.15 -5346X_{\mbox{YearBuilt}} + 4148.61X_{\mbox{HomeSize}} + 265131.89X_{\mbox{Townhouse}} \\ + 596166.09X_{\mbox{House}} -54264.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro}} -158852.92X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:Townhouse}} \\ -642515.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:House}} \]

Test for Significance of Interaction

# Reduced model and summary
red_model <- lm(Price ~ YearBuilt+BuildingArea+Type_Townhouse+Type_House+NorthMetro, data=data)
red_coef <- coefficients(red_model)
red_anova <- anova(red_model)
red_summary <- summary(red_model)
red_ci <- as_tibble(confint(red_model, level=0.95))
red_t <- as_tibble(red_summary[[4]])
int_anova <- anova(red_model, model)

Hypotheses

   \(H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 =0\) (The interaction should be dropped)
   \(H_1: \beta_1 \space or \space \beta_2 \ne 0\) (The interaction should not be dropped)

Test Statistic

   \(F_0 = 141.25\).

p-value

   \(p < 0.0001\).

Rejection Region

   Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

   Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that the interaction is significant and should not be dropped.

Testing for Dropping two Continuous Predictors

# Reduced model and summary
red_model <- lm(Price ~ Type_Townhouse+Type_House+NorthMetro+NorthMetro:Type_Townhouse+NorthMetro:Type_House, data=data)
red_coef <- coefficients(red_model)
red_anova <- anova(red_model)
red_summary <- summary(red_model)
red_ci <- as_tibble(confint(red_model, level=0.95))
red_t <- as_tibble(red_summary[[4]])
int_anova <- anova(red_model, model)

Hypotheses

   \(H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 =0\) (The predictors should be dropped)
   \(H_1: \beta_1 \space or \space \beta_2 \ne 0\) (The predictors should not be dropped)

Test Statistic

   \(F_0 = 691.19\).

p-value

   \(p < 0.0001\).

Rejection Region

   Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Conclusion and Interpretation

   Reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that the continuous predictors should not be dropped from the model.

Reconstructed Regression Line

Since all of the above tests showed that none of the tested predictors should not be dropped, the regression line remains the same as the full model above.

Testing for Significance of Remaining Individual Predictors

   Reject if \(p < \alpha\), where \(\alpha=0.05\).

Final Model

One predictor was found to not be significant. However, I am going to keep north metro in the model. This is because it is included in higher order effects that were deemed significant. If north metro is removed, then the higher order terms must also be removed.

The final regression model is \[ \hat{Y} = 10911432.15 -5346X_{\mbox{YearBuilt}} + 4148.61X_{\mbox{HomeSize}} + 265131.89X_{\mbox{Townhouse}} \\ + 596166.09X_{\mbox{House}} -54264.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro}} -158852.92X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:Townhouse}} \\ -642515.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:House}} \]

Interpretation of Final Model

  • For each increase in the year built, the price decreases by 5346 dollars.
  • For an increase in the home size, the price increases by 4148.61 dollars.
  • If the home is a townhouse, the price is 265131.89 dollars more than an apartment.
  • If the home is a house, the price is 596166.09 dollars more than an apartment.
  • If the home is located in the north metro, the price decreases by 54264.76 dollars.
  • If a townhouse is in the north metro, the price decreases by an additional 158852.92 dollars.
  • If a house is in the north metro, the price decreases by an additional 642515.76 dollars.

Model visualizations

Here are some plots to help visualize the results of the model. Each plot shows a continuous predictor vs price. The original data is shown as a scatter plot, and overlaid is predicted values from the model corresponding to different categorical predictor combinations.

data$pred_price_yearbuilt_townhouse_north <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea) + coef[[4]] + coef[[6]] + coef[[7]]
data$pred_price_yearbuilt_townhouse_south <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea) + coef[[4]]
data$pred_price_yearbuilt_house_south <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea) + coef[[5]]
data$pred_price_yearbuilt_house_north <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea) + coef[[5]] + coef[[6]] + coef[[8]]
data$pred_price_yearbuilt_apa_south <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea)
data$pred_price_yearbuilt_apa_north <- coef[[1]] + coef[[2]]*(data$YearBuilt) + coef[[3]]*mean(data$BuildingArea) + coef[[6]]

Overall I think this model is a good predictor of price. The results are mostly as expected with a house in the north being the most expensive, followed by townhouses and then apartments. The interesting result is that houses in the south metropolitan area are predicted to cost the least of out all home types and locations. Maybe some further exploration and some more significant predictors can help explain the prices of houses in the south metro area.
